<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="229" type="3.2. cladistic analysis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="229">3.2. Cladistic analysis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="229">
The unconstrained MP analysis produced one most parsimonious tree (549 steps); the tree with support values is shown in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 12–14" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 12 - 14. Unconstrained-MP analyses, most parsimonious tree (549 steps) with Bremer and Bootstrap values of support (12); Constrained-MP analyses, forcing Chaetarthriinae monophyly (13); unconstrained-BI analysis with homoplasy as partitioning scheme and mapped posterior probabilities (pp)." figureDoi="10.3897/asp.80.e76826.figures12-14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/704684" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">12</figureCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chaetarthriinae">Chaetarthriinae</taxonomicName>
appears as non-monophyletic, with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Chaetarthria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chaetarthria" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Chaetarthria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
branching early on. The remaining genera of 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chaetarthriinae">Chaetarthriinae</taxonomicName>
cluster in one clade but including 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Paracymus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paracymus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Paracymus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1884" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Tormus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tormus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Tormus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Hydrophilinae">Hydrophilinae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" rank="tribe" tribe="Laccobiini">Laccobiini</taxonomicName>
). The tribes 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bedel" authorityYear="1881" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" rank="tribe" tribe="Chaetarthriini">Chaetarthriini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" rank="tribe" tribe="Anacaenini">Anacaenini</taxonomicName>
were not recovered as monophyletic. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spangler" authorityYear="1986" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Guyanobius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Guyanobius" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Guyanobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears with low support as the sister group of the 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" rank="tribe" tribe="Anacaenini">Anacaenini</taxonomicName>
(( 
<taxonomicName authorityName="M.Hansen" authorityYear="1999" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Pseudorygmodus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudorygmodus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Pseudorygmodus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bedel" authorityYear="1881" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Crenitis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crenitis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Crenitis</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Winters" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Crenitulus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crenitulus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Crenitulus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
)), and forms a clade with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Paracymus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paracymus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Paracymus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1884" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Tormus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tormus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Tormus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which diverge earlier into two successive branches.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="229">
Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 15. Detail of the tree that includes Chaetarthriinae with synapomorphies mapped. Characters in red indicate unique transformations; characters in white indicate homoplasious transformations." figureDoi="10.3897/asp.80.e76826.figure15" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/704685" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">15</figureCitation>
shows a detailed diagram of the 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chaetarthriinae">Chaetarthriinae</taxonomicName>
clade with the synapomorphies mapped on it. The complete most parsimonious tree with all synapomorphies is shown in Supplementary file 5.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="229">
To test if the resultant topology of the unconstrained analysis was not affected by the inclusion of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Paracymus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paracymus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Paracymus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1884" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Tormus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tormus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Tormus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, we performed a constrained MP forcing 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chaetarthriinae">Chaetarthriinae</taxonomicName>
monophyly. This analysis generated two most parsimonious trees (554 steps) with no differences in the divergence patterns for the subfamily; a detail of the 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chaetarthriinae">Chaetarthriinae</taxonomicName>
clade is shown in Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 12–14" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 12 - 14. Unconstrained-MP analyses, most parsimonious tree (549 steps) with Bremer and Bootstrap values of support (12); Constrained-MP analyses, forcing Chaetarthriinae monophyly (13); unconstrained-BI analysis with homoplasy as partitioning scheme and mapped posterior probabilities (pp)." figureDoi="10.3897/asp.80.e76826.figures12-14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/704684" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">13</figureCitation>
. In this case, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spangler" authorityYear="1986" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Guyanobius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Guyanobius" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Guyanobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears nested within 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" rank="tribe" tribe="Anacaenini">Anacaenini</taxonomicName>
, forming a cluster with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bedel" authorityYear="1881" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Crenitis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crenitis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Crenitis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Winters" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Crenitulus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crenitulus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Crenitulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="229">
The unconstrained BI with homoplasy as a partitioning scheme does not recover neither the subfamily nor the tribes as monophyletic (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 12–14" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 12 - 14. Unconstrained-MP analyses, most parsimonious tree (549 steps) with Bremer and Bootstrap values of support (12); Constrained-MP analyses, forcing Chaetarthriinae monophyly (13); unconstrained-BI analysis with homoplasy as partitioning scheme and mapped posterior probabilities (pp)." figureDoi="10.3897/asp.80.e76826.figures12-14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/704684" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">14</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Chaetarthria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chaetarthria" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Chaetarthria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears as a basal taxon, sister to all taxa included, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spangler" authorityYear="1986" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Guyanobius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Guyanobius" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Guyanobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is revealed to be nested within 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" rank="tribe" tribe="Anacaenini">Anacaenini</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spangler" authorityYear="1986" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Guyanobius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Guyanobius" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Guyanobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clustered with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bedel" authorityYear="1881" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Crenitis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crenitis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Crenitis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Winters" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Crenitulus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Crenitulus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Crenitulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with a rather high support (pp=0.94) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="M.Hansen" authorityYear="1999" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Pseudorygmodus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudorygmodus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="229">Pseudorygmodus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears as sister group of all of them.
</paragraph>
